            },
            "answer_text": "If you don\u2019t get found out then yes, you will earn roughly \u00a34 per 1,000 streams \u2014 but I wouldn\u2019t recommend doing it. Spotify can work out if an artist is abusing the system, and they can take your music down if you are doing something that goes against what they deem fair usage. From a moral perspective, reaching 1,000 or more plays organically and legitimately is much more satisfying anyway. You also need to think about it as an active live performer if you do so. Imagine if you have 25,000 plays on one song but the attendances at your shows don\u2019t reflect the song\u2019s popularity \u2014 promoters, venues and booking agents will stop booking you for shows. Instead you can pitch your music to playlist curators to help your song\u2019s plays increase organically. This will also help you potentially reach new fans. Be careful though as some curators buy followers to make their playlist look more popular than it is, then charge you to feature on it \u2014 do not ever pay to appear on a playlist as this will likely not see your song gain any organic plays or generate any royalties. ",
